gh yielding variety. Second highest yield after Chandler in many trials.", "growing_notes": "", "availability": ""}, {"name": "Mara des Bois", "slug": "mara-des-bois", "lineage_type": "hybrid", "climate_slug": "humid-subtropical", "sort_order": 13, "origin": "France (Jacques Marionnet), 1991. Lineage: (Gento × Ostara) × (Red Gauntlet × Korona)", "traits": "Everbearing variety with intense wild strawberry aroma. Small to medium berries (11-16g). Round to slightly conical shape.", "flesh_fruit": "Exceptional flavor - highest rated among everbearers. Intense aroma reminiscent of wild strawberries. Glossy red exterior, red flesh. Melting texture combining firmness of conventional with tenderness of wild strawberry.", "yield_notes": "Moderate yield but superior quality. Produces throughout the season. Lower yielding specialty variety.", "growing_notes": "", "availability": "Available from select Australian nurseries, specialty berry suppliers, and online retailers. Popular home garden variety."}, {"name": "Cambridge Rival", "slug": "cambridge-rival", "lineage_type": "heirloom", "climate_slug": "humid-subtropical", "sort_order": 14, "origin": "Cambridge, UK, mid-1900s. Cross between ''Dorset'' and ''Early Cambridge'' (both old UK varieties)", "traits": "Historic heirloom variety, once widely available in Australia. Saved from obscurity by Diggers Club.", "flesh_fruit": "Considered by many to be the best tasting strawberry in Australia. Superior flavor to modern varieties.", "yield_notes": "Good home garden production. Long fruiting period.", "growing_notes": "", "availability": ""}, {"name": "San Andreas", "slug": "san-andreas", "lineage_type": "hybrid", "climate_slug": "humid-subtropical", "sort_order": 15, "origin": "University of California, USA, 2001", "traits": "Day-neutral variety. High quality fruit produced early in season. Slightly lighter color than Albion.", "flesh_fruit": "Very sweet with similar flavor profile to Albion. Found to be one of the sweetest varieties in trials.", "yield_notes": "High yields with good early production. Continuous fruiting through season.", "growing_notes": "", "availability": ""}, {"name": "Alexandria", "slug": "alexandria", "lineage_type": "heirloom", "climate_slug": "humid-subtropical", "sort_order": 16, "origin": "Europe, heirloom alpine variety referenced in 19th century literature", "traits": "Small, elongated red berries (~1 inch long × 0.5 inch wide). Clumping variety, produces no runners. Compact plants to 20cm tall.", "flesh_fruit": "Exceptional flavor with signature wild strawberry taste - bright and rich. Sweet-tart with intense aromatics.", "yield_notes": "Everbearing, produces continuously June-September. Fruits in first year from seed.", "growing_notes": "", "availability": ""}, {"name": "Yellow Wonder (White Soul)", "slug": "yellow-wonder-white-soul", "lineage_type": "heirloom", "climate_slug": "humid-subtropical", "sort_order": 17, "origin": "Europe, heirloom alpine variety", "traits": "Oblong yellow/white berries. Small spreading plants to 15cm tall. Less attractive to birds than red varieties.", "flesh_fruit": "Luscious pineapple-vanilla flavor with rosy-floral aromatics. Very aromatic with hints of tropical fruits. Intensely sweet.", "yield_notes": "Everbearing, clumping variety. Continuous production through growing season.", "growing_notes": "", "availability": ""}, {"name": "Mignonette", "slug": "mignonette", "lineage_type": "heirloom", "climate_slug": "humid-subtropical", "sort_order": 18, "origin": "European alpine variety, heritage selection", "traits": "Compact variety producing masses of tiny sweet strawberries. Runner-less, forming neat clumps.", "flesh_fruit": "Small red berries with intense wild strawberry flavor. Very sweet and aromatic.", "yield_notes": "Prolific producer of small berries throughout summer. Heavy bearer for size.", "growing_notes": "", "availability": "Seeds from specialty alpine strawberry suppliers, heirloom seed companies."}, {"name": "Baron